        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much does a 7-day group trip to Oahu cost per person?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Budget $150–$250 per person per day all-in for a comfortable group trip to Oahu. That covers accommodation split between 4–6 people, food, activities, and transport. A 7-day trip typically runs $1,050–$1,750 per person excluding flights. Flights from the US mainland add $300–$600 depending on origin and timing. The biggest savings come from splitting vacation rentals rather than booking individual hotel rooms."}
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Do you need a rental car for a week in Oahu?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "You only need a rental car for two days: the North Shore day trip and the Kailua/windward side day. For everything else in Waikiki and Honolulu, rideshare (Uber/Lyft) and walking work fine. Renting just for those two days costs roughly $80–$120 total split between the group, far cheaper than a full-week rental plus the parking headaches in Waikiki."}
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "When is the best time to visit Oahu with a group of friends?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "April–June and September–October are the best times to visit Oahu with a group. These shoulder seasons offer lighter crowds, accommodation prices 15–25% lower than peak, and consistently sunny weather with water temperatures around 78°F. Summer (July–August) is peak season — still great but book further ahead and expect higher prices. Winter (November–March) brings whale sightings and spectacular North Shore surf, but many beaches are spectator-only during big swell."}
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How far in advance should you book Hanauma Bay?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Book Hanauma Bay 2–5 days in advance, ideally a week out during peak summer season. Tickets go on sale at 7am Hawaii time exactly two days before each date at hawaii.gowaiver.com. Walk-ins are not permitted. The entry fee is $25 per person for non-residents. Arrive when the bay opens (8am) to see the most marine life before afternoon crowds affect water clarity."}
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is Oahu good for large groups of 6 or more people?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes, Oahu works very well for large groups of 6 or more, but advance planning matters. Book vacation rentals in the Ala Moana area instead of hotel rooms — shared living space and a kitchen make coordination much easier and cut costs significantly. For restaurants, always call ahead for groups of 6+. Activities like surf lessons, kayak rentals, and the North Shore shrimp trucks all handle large groups comfortably."}
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the best beach in Oahu for groups?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Kailua Beach on the windward side is consistently rated the best beach on Oahu for groups — calm turquoise water, almost no current, and easy kayak access to the Mokulua Islands. For snorkeling with a group, Hanauma Bay is the top choice (book ahead). For surf lessons and central location, Kaimana Beach (Sans Souci) at the quiet end of Waikiki offers calmer water and fewer crowds than the main Waikiki strip."}
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the best restaurant in Oahu for a group dinner?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "MW Restaurant on Beretania Street is the top pick for a special group dinner — refined local Hawaiian cuisine, an optional tasting menu, and exceptional desserts. Budget $80–$120 per person. For a more casual but equally celebrated option, The Pig and the Lady in Chinatown serves Vietnamese-inspired local food and runs $45–$70 per person. Both require reservations at least a week out for groups."}
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What should you book before arriving in Oahu?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Three things are non-negotiable to pre-book before arriving in Oahu: (1) Hanauma Bay snorkeling tickets at hawaii.gowaiver.com — they sell out 2–5 days ahead and walk-ins are not allowed; (2) at least one dinner reservation at The Pig and the Lady or MW Restaurant — both fill up a week or more out for groups; (3) transport for the North Shore day trip — either a rental car ($50–$80/day) or a shuttle through Roberts Hawaii."}
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How long does the Diamond Head hike take?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The Diamond Head hike takes approximately 1.5 to 2 hours round trip for most groups. The trail is 1.6 miles round trip with an elevation gain of about 560 feet. It is not technically difficult but does involve some stairs and a tunnel section. Go before 7:30am to beat the heat and the crowds. Entry is $5 per person."}
      }
    ]
  }
